1521
01:22:39,760 --> 01:22:41,760
from the research carried out by Pons,

1522
01:22:41,760 --> 01:22:44,720
which are presented in Crawford Knott's paper,

1523
01:22:44,720 --> 01:22:48,240
and then completely ignores Crawford Knott's experiment in the school,

1524
01:22:48,240 --> 01:22:50,960
which reported results above the white norm.

1525
01:22:51,600 --> 01:22:55,840
The entire point of Crawford Knott's paper goes totally unmentioned by Lin,

1526
01:22:55,840 --> 01:23:00,240
who simply extracts the data that he wants and discards the rest.

1527
01:23:00,240 --> 01:23:03,360
He had data showing a black African test score

1528
01:23:03,360 --> 01:23:05,120
that was above the white norm,

1529
01:23:05,120 --> 01:23:08,000
and he simply decided to ignore it.

1530
01:23:08,000 --> 01:23:10,320
Also, like the previous paper we discussed,

1531
01:23:10,320 --> 01:23:14,560
this study did not report IQ scores for the testees.

1532
01:23:14,560 --> 01:23:16,400
Those are simply concocted by Lin

1533
01:23:16,400 --> 01:23:18,880
out of the Raven's progressive matrices data,

1534
01:23:18,880 --> 01:23:23,120
using a sophisticated statistical technique called guessing.

1535
01:23:23,120 --> 01:23:24,960
So to understand what Lin has done here,

1536
01:23:24,960 --> 01:23:29,200
we need to talk a little about IQ test construction and standardization.

1537
01:23:29,200 --> 01:23:31,200
And let's start with the bell curve.

1538
01:23:31,840 --> 01:23:35,520
Not the book this time, but the statistical distribution.

1539
01:23:35,520 --> 01:23:41,040
Now, IQ tests, as we know, return this bell curve, or normal distribution.

1540
01:23:41,040 --> 01:23:44,800
This means that the majority of the scores are clustered around the middle

1541
01:23:44,800 --> 01:23:48,560
and taper off towards the ends of the curve in a symmetrical way.

1542
01:23:49,120 --> 01:23:53,280
But why, you might ask, do they actually return this distribution?

1543
01:23:53,280 --> 01:23:55,520
Well, it's because that's how they're designed.

1544
01:23:56,080 --> 01:24:00,800
Psychometricians design IQ tests so that their results match the bell curve.

1545
01:24:00,800 --> 01:24:03,040
If the test they design is too easy,

1546
01:24:03,040 --> 01:24:04,880
then the bell curve will lean to the right,

1547
01:24:04,880 --> 01:24:07,120
as too many people will get high scores.

1548
01:24:07,680 --> 01:24:10,240
If the test is too hard, it will lean to the left,

1549
01:24:10,240 --> 01:24:12,480
as too many people get low scores.

1550
01:24:12,480 --> 01:24:16,400
And if the test doesn't differentiate between people to the right degree,

1551
01:24:16,400 --> 01:24:19,840
then too many people could be at either end of the curve.

1552
01:24:19,840 --> 01:24:23,520
So the test designers tinker with the difficulty of the test

1553
01:24:23,520 --> 01:24:25,840
until the results match the bell curve.

1554
01:24:26,400 --> 01:24:28,960
So why do psychometricians do this?

1555
01:24:28,960 --> 01:24:32,240
Well, it's because that's how they assume intelligence is distributed

1556
01:24:32,240 --> 01:24:34,000
throughout the human population.

1557
01:24:34,640 --> 01:24:36,880
Emphasis on assume here,

1558
01:24:36,880 --> 01:24:40,400
because we do not actually know how intelligence is distributed

1559
01:24:40,400 --> 01:24:42,160
throughout the human population.

1560
01:24:42,160 --> 01:24:44,800
Unless you specifically design for it,

1561
01:24:44,800 --> 01:24:48,720
tests do not necessarily return a bell curve distribution.

1562
01:24:48,720 --> 01:24:49,840
For example here,

1563
01:24:49,840 --> 01:24:53,280
the armed forces qualifying test used in the bell curve

1564
01:24:53,280 --> 01:24:55,840
did not return a bell curve distribution.

1565
01:24:55,840 --> 01:25:01,200
It was, after all, designed to test readiness to join the armed forces, not IQ.

1566
01:25:01,200 --> 01:25:05,040
As a result, it does not differentiate between people to a large enough degree,

1567
01:25:05,040 --> 01:25:09,120
so Hernstein and Murray, to make the results conform to a bell curve,

1568
01:25:09,120 --> 01:25:11,280
recalculated the scores.

1569
01:25:11,360 --> 01:25:16,080
Here is a graph of the raw AFQT scores overlaid with Hernstein and Murray's

1570
01:25:16,080 --> 01:25:20,400
recalculated bell curve scores from the book Inequality by Design.

1571
01:25:20,400 --> 01:25:23,920
And as we can see, too many people scored too highly on the test

1572
01:25:23,920 --> 01:25:26,400
and there isn't enough differentiation between people

1573
01:25:26,400 --> 01:25:28,800
on the upper end of the scale in particular.

1574
01:25:28,800 --> 01:25:30,160
So yes, that's right.

1575
01:25:30,160 --> 01:25:31,840
In the book The Bell Curve,

1576
01:25:31,840 --> 01:25:35,120
the principal intelligence test the authors use as a source

1577
01:25:35,120 --> 01:25:37,600
did not return a bell curve distribution.

1578
01:25:37,600 --> 01:25:40,240
To transform these results into a bell curve,

1579
01:25:40,240 --> 01:25:44,800
Hernstein and Murray exaggerated the slight differences at the end of the scale.

1580
01:25:44,800 --> 01:25:48,880
They basically gave extra credit for being near the tails of the bell curve

1581
01:25:48,880 --> 01:25:51,120
and less for being in the middle.

1582
01:25:51,120 --> 01:25:55,600
They did this as they explain in Appendix 2 to correct for skew.

1583
01:25:55,600 --> 01:25:58,880
But remember, in relation to how intelligence is distributed

1584
01:25:58,880 --> 01:26:00,720
throughout the human population,

1585
01:26:00,720 --> 01:26:03,120
these results are only actually skewed

1586
01:26:03,120 --> 01:26:07,760
if we assume that intelligence is distributed in a bell curve to begin with.

1587
01:26:07,760 --> 01:26:09,520
This is circular logic.

1588
01:26:09,520 --> 01:26:12,880
We are assuming the result that we are going to get beforehand

1589
01:26:12,880 --> 01:26:16,480
and then designing the test or just manipulating the data

1590
01:26:16,480 --> 01:26:18,560
in order to reach that conclusion.

1591
01:26:18,560 --> 01:26:20,400
Anyway, to get back on track here,

1592
01:26:20,400 --> 01:26:25,120
what does all this have to do with Richard Lin and the Raven's progressive matrices test?

1593
01:26:25,120 --> 01:26:29,280
Well, that test also does not return a bell curve distribution.

1594
01:26:29,280 --> 01:26:32,640
The results are not symmetrically distributed around their mean,

1595
01:26:32,640 --> 01:26:35,600
to quote an article by psychologist Leon Kamin.

1596
01:26:35,600 --> 01:26:39,200
That article also notes that the test's developer, John Raven,

1597
01:26:39,200 --> 01:26:44,480
always insisted that the progressive matrices scores cannot be converted into IQs.

1598
01:26:44,480 --> 01:26:47,760
Here is an example of the distribution of matrix test scores

1599
01:26:47,760 --> 01:26:52,240
from Raven's paper, Standardization of Progressive Matrices 1938.

1600
01:26:52,240 --> 01:26:56,240
And as you can see, those are some very wobbly bell curves right there.

1601
01:26:56,240 --> 01:27:01,120
What the test does give is raw scores which correspond to percentile scores.

1602
01:27:01,120 --> 01:27:05,120
So you can know from your raw score how you compare percentile-wise

1603
01:27:05,120 --> 01:27:07,680
to the group on which the test was normalized.

1604
01:27:07,760 --> 01:27:13,040
But these percentiles will not be distributed evenly around their mean in a bell curve.

1605
01:27:13,040 --> 01:27:17,680
To calculate IQ, Richard Lin takes the average of these raw scores,

1606
01:27:17,680 --> 01:27:20,000
converts them to a percentile score,

1607
01:27:20,000 --> 01:27:24,720
and then gives what the IQ of that percentile score would correspond to

1608
01:27:24,720 --> 01:27:28,240
if the results were in a bell curve distribution.

1609
01:27:28,240 --> 01:27:32,560
Basically, Lin is assuming a bell curve exists where there demonstrably isn't one

1610
01:27:32,560 --> 01:27:34,800
and is forcing the data to fit it.

1611
01:27:34,800 --> 01:27:38,480
Another issue here is that in the decades since the Second World War,

1612
01:27:38,480 --> 01:27:43,760
scores on the Raven's matrices test similar to IQ test scores had been changing.

1613
01:27:43,760 --> 01:27:47,200
Accordingly, the test had been standardized several times.

1614
01:27:47,200 --> 01:27:51,200
So when we're comparing the African results with Western norms,

1615
01:27:51,200 --> 01:27:54,080
we need to identify what norm group we're using

1616
01:27:54,080 --> 01:27:59,280
because comparisons with different groups from different times could give different results.

1617
01:27:59,280 --> 01:28:04,000
Particularly sharp-eyed viewers would have noticed that Lin does exactly this

1618
01:28:04,000 --> 01:28:06,320
in the quote from his 2002 book,

1619
01:28:06,320 --> 01:28:09,200
IQ and the Wealth of Nations, which I showed earlier,

1620
01:28:09,200 --> 01:28:12,160
where he discusses Nigerian IQs, quote,

1621
01:28:12,160 --> 01:28:16,000
in terms of the British 1979 standardization.

1622
01:28:16,560 --> 01:28:19,600
Identifying this standardization is important,

1623
01:28:19,600 --> 01:28:25,040
as using a different one could lead to a different Nigerian IQ being calculated.

1624
01:28:25,040 --> 01:28:29,520
In his 1991 review of the literature cited in the bell curve, however,

1625
01:28:29,520 --> 01:28:35,440
Lin does not identify what standardization he's using for the various tests he is comparing.

1626
01:28:35,440 --> 01:28:38,640
What this means is that there is a gap in Lin's calculations

1627
01:28:38,640 --> 01:28:42,480
that can only be filled by faith in his academic honesty,

1628
01:28:42,480 --> 01:28:44,720
which Hearnstein and Murray clearly have,

1629
01:28:44,720 --> 01:28:47,520
