01:33:41,600 --> 01:33:44,240
picked one that was sort of near the middle,

1718
01:33:44,240 --> 01:33:46,960
and said that's the average Black African IQ.

1719
01:33:47,600 --> 01:33:49,920
This is outrageous.

1720
01:33:49,920 --> 01:33:51,440
It is a crime.

1721
01:33:51,440 --> 01:33:54,720
It might actually be a crime, and if it's not, it should be.

1722
01:33:54,720 --> 01:33:57,600
Now, I am far from the first person to criticize

1723
01:33:57,600 --> 01:34:00,480
the Bell Curve's reliance upon Richard Lin as a source.

1724
01:34:00,960 --> 01:34:04,960
Various academics were already well aware of Lin and his dodgy data,

1725
01:34:04,960 --> 01:34:07,040
so when Herrnstein and Murray cited him,

1726
01:34:07,040 --> 01:34:11,840
they were immediately attacked with accusations of bias and racism.

1727
01:34:11,840 --> 01:34:15,840
Charles Murray responds to these attacks in the afterword to the Bell Curve,

1728
01:34:15,840 --> 01:34:17,520
and his defense is laughable.

1729
01:34:17,520 --> 01:34:20,800
His first defense is to say that the topic of African IQ

1730
01:34:20,800 --> 01:34:26,080
is a tiny piece of the Bell Curve, three paragraphs on pages 288 to 89,

1731
01:34:26,080 --> 01:34:29,520
and in regards to this, two responses jump to mind immediately.

1732
01:34:29,600 --> 01:34:34,160
The first is to say, well, maybe you should have spent longer on it then, Charles.

1733
01:34:34,160 --> 01:34:36,000
We were wrong very quickly.

1734
01:34:36,000 --> 01:34:38,640
Isn't a defense against being wrong, is it?

1735
01:34:38,640 --> 01:34:40,400
Maybe if you put a little more effort in,

1736
01:34:40,400 --> 01:34:43,520
you would have seen that Lin's paper was a load of rubbish.

1737
01:34:43,520 --> 01:34:48,160
Secondly, this part of the Bell Curve is far more important than Murray makes out.

1738
01:34:48,160 --> 01:34:51,200
He uses Lin's paper to dismiss the arguments

1739
01:34:51,200 --> 01:34:55,360
that black-white differences in IQ are caused by environmental factors,

1740
01:34:55,360 --> 01:34:57,120
such as a history of oppression,

1741
01:34:57,120 --> 01:34:59,920
which is the single most common counterargument

1742
01:34:59,920 --> 01:35:02,880
to one of the principal claims in the entire book.

1743
01:35:02,880 --> 01:35:07,440
At no point does Murray actually address any specific criticisms of Lin's work

1744
01:35:07,440 --> 01:35:09,520
or any of its various errors.

1745
01:35:09,520 --> 01:35:14,560
He mainly just seems outraged that anyone dares to have criticized him at all, to be honest.

1746
01:35:14,560 --> 01:35:17,280
And it's exactly this sort of academic laziness

1747
01:35:17,280 --> 01:35:20,480
that fed much of the angry response to the Bell Curve.

1748
01:35:20,480 --> 01:35:23,600
Murray refuses to admit that citing Lin was a mistake,

1749
01:35:23,600 --> 01:35:28,720
and simply throws out some newer studies that supposedly show he was right anyway.

1750
01:35:28,720 --> 01:35:29,760
So there.

1751
01:35:29,760 --> 01:35:32,000
This speaks to a couple of things.

1752
01:35:32,000 --> 01:35:36,320
Firstly, it is a fatal underestimation of exactly how badly this damages

1753
01:35:36,320 --> 01:35:40,000
the faith that a reader of the Bell Curve can have in its authors.

1754
01:35:40,000 --> 01:35:43,120
After all, this is not the only time they cite Richard Lin.

1755
01:35:43,120 --> 01:35:46,240
He has more than 20 citations in their bibliography,

1756
01:35:46,240 --> 01:35:49,040
and they thank him specifically in the acknowledgments.

1757
01:35:49,040 --> 01:35:53,520
If this is the sort of data that Charles Murray is willing to accept as legitimate,

1758
01:35:53,520 --> 01:35:56,800
how can we trust anything he says anywhere in the book?

1759
01:35:56,800 --> 01:36:00,320
How can we trust the new studies he brings up to defend Richard Lin?

1760
01:36:00,960 --> 01:36:05,920
Personally, I think it would be a mistake to even look at these new studies.

1761
01:36:05,920 --> 01:36:09,360
Murray's response to having his previous sources called into question

1762
01:36:09,360 --> 01:36:11,760
is to simply throw out new sources.

1763
01:36:11,760 --> 01:36:16,400
His response to having these called into question would no doubt be to throw out more.

1764
01:36:16,400 --> 01:36:20,560
The responsibility for checking whether his sources are trustworthy or accurate

1765
01:36:20,560 --> 01:36:23,760
has been moved from Murray to his critics.

1766
01:36:23,760 --> 01:36:26,160
They're the ones doing the reading and the fact-checking,

1767
01:36:26,160 --> 01:36:28,800
whereas he never gets held to account.

1768
01:36:28,800 --> 01:36:34,000
So long as we all understand that, however, I suppose we can take a brief peek.

1769
01:36:34,000 --> 01:36:35,200
So, Murray says,

1770
01:36:35,200 --> 01:36:40,880
Let me turn to two studies post-dating Richard Lin's review that we cite on page 289.

1771
01:36:40,880 --> 01:36:43,600
One was a South African study led by Kenneth Owen,

1772
01:36:43,600 --> 01:36:48,320
published in the refereed British journal Personality and Individual Differences.

1773
01:36:48,320 --> 01:36:52,320
So this was the suitability of Raven's standard progressive matrices

1774
01:36:52,320 --> 01:36:54,480
for various groups in South Africa,

1775
01:36:54,480 --> 01:36:58,080
a paper that was published in 1992.

1776
01:36:58,080 --> 01:37:01,280
So we are still in apartheid South Africa.

1777
01:37:01,280 --> 01:37:04,960
And this study tested black students from the KwaZulu region,

1778
01:37:04,960 --> 01:37:08,080
the same as one of the studies from Richard Lin's review.

1779
01:37:08,080 --> 01:37:10,080
It even has the same author.

1780
01:37:10,080 --> 01:37:13,680
So this is not a great showing with the first study here.

1781
01:37:13,680 --> 01:37:16,080
Murray introduces the other study by saying,

1782
01:37:16,160 --> 01:37:18,480
The second example of a recent careful study

1783
01:37:18,480 --> 01:37:22,800
was conducted by a black scholar, Fred Cindy, and published in The Psychologist.

1784
01:37:22,800 --> 01:37:25,920
It matched 204 black Zimbabwean pupils

1785
01:37:25,920 --> 01:37:29,600
and 202 white English students from London inner-city schools

1786
01:37:29,600 --> 01:37:34,240
for age, 12 to 14 years old, sex, and educational level,

1787
01:37:34,240 --> 01:37:37,200
both samples being characterized as working class,

1788
01:37:37,200 --> 01:37:39,920
and then goes on to say that the white students from London

1789
01:37:39,920 --> 01:37:44,240
got higher test results than the black students from Zimbabwe.

1790
01:37:44,240 --> 01:37:48,800
However, Murray takes the cue from Richard Lin and leaves out all the context.

1791
01:37:48,800 --> 01:37:53,440
The main thing here being that Zimbabwe was a British colony known as Rhodesia

1792
01:37:53,440 --> 01:37:58,720
until it gained independence in 1980, following a 15-year civil war.

1793
01:37:59,280 --> 01:38:03,280
Rhodesia was a discriminatory racially segregated state.

1794
01:38:03,280 --> 01:38:09,360
12 to 14-year-olds in 1994 would have been born around the time of Zimbabwe's independence

1795
01:38:09,360 --> 01:38:14,080
to parents who were raised and educated in a segregated British colony.

1796
01:38:14,320 --> 01:38:18,560
Which makes the comparison to the children of London as all the more ridiculous here.

1797
01:38:18,560 --> 01:38:21,680
The children of the colonized country are being measured

1798
01:38:21,680 --> 01:38:24,480
against the children of the colonizing country.

1799
01:38:24,480 --> 01:38:27,040
Fred Cindy, the professor who offered the study,

1800
01:38:27,040 --> 01:38:30,080
more recently spoke about his earlier work in the following way.

1801
01:38:30,720 --> 01:38:33,760
For many years, African countries have depended upon the use

1802
01:38:33,760 --> 01:38:36,080
of Western-designed psychometric instruments

1803
01:38:36,080 --> 01:38:39,920
such as Raven's progressive matrices and some others.

1804
01:38:39,920 --> 01:38:44,720
Such tests, standardized in Western cultures using Western cultural values,

1805
01:38:44,720 --> 01:38:47,600
have been found to be useful to a certain extent.

1806
01:38:47,600 --> 01:38:51,760
In many cases, interpretation of results from Western-designed tests

1807
01:38:51,760 --> 01:38:57,120
have however been distorted to suit Western stereotypes about other nations.

1808
01:38:57,120 --> 01:38:59,120
Cindy 1994.

1809
01:38:59,120 --> 01:39:03,680
A very important point which Lin and Murray would do well to take on board.

1810
01:39:04,240 --> 01:39:08,560
Murray reveals a misunderstanding of the criticisms raised against the bell curve

1811
01:39:08,560 --> 01:39:12,000
when he goes on to say that the problem is not as often alleged

1812
01:39:12,000 --> 01:39:14,880
that such studies are written by racists.

1813
01:39:14,880 --> 01:39:16,640
In the two instances just cited,

1814
01:39:16,640 --> 01:39:21,040
a charge belied by Owen's scholarly reputation and by Cindy's race,

1815
01:39:21,040 --> 01:39:24,000
but that the African story is still so incomplete.

1816
01:39:24,640 --> 01:39:26,240
What Murray gets wrong here,

1817
01:39:26,240 --> 01:39:29,200
beyond the implication that a scholarly reputation

1818
01:39:29,200 --> 01:39:32,000
could not also be accompanied by racism,

1819
01:39:32,000 --> 01:39:36,160
is that the allegation is not that these studies are written by racists.

1820
01:39:36,160 --> 01:39:39,280
It's that the studies are being deliberately misinterpreted

1821
01:39:39,280 --> 01:39:42,080
and misrepresented by racists.

1822
01:39:42,080 --> 01:39:44,000
Racists like Richard Lin,

1823
01:39:44,000 --> 01:39:46,960
who stripped from the studies all context and analysis

1824
01:39:46,960 --> 01:39:49,840
and used them to push a racist worldview.

1825
01:39:49,840 --> 01:39:53,520
Murray fails to see that the problem is not that it is impossible

1826
01:39:53,520 --> 01:39:58,000
to find other studies that have similar results to the ones cited in the bell curve.

1827
01:39:58,000 --> 01:40:03,200
It's that he's willing to treat data collected in a segregated white supremacist state

1828
01:40:03,200 --> 01:40:08,000
as a legitimate source to inform us about inherent racial differences.

1829
01:40:08,000 --> 01:40:09,840
That is the issue here.

1830
01:40:09,840 --> 01:40:11,120
On a more general note,

1831
01:40:11,120 --> 01:40:14,240
what Murray writes in the afterword and how he writes it

1832
01:40:14,240 --> 01:40:16,880
shows us exactly how little respect he has

1833
01:40:16,880 --> 01:40:19,680
for what should be treated as a sensitive topic.

1834
01:40:20,240 --> 01:40:23,120
The subject of his writing is potential differences

1835
01:40:23,120 --> 01:40:25,920
in native ability between racial groups,

1836
01:40:25,920 --> 01:40:29,360
and discussing that requires a level of tact and consideration

1837
01:40:29,360 --> 01:40:31,680
that is totally absent here.

1838
01:40:31,680 --> 01:40:35,120
You cannot half-ass the science with this stuff.

1839
01:40:35,120 --> 01:40:39,920
Murray's refusal to respond directly to criticism of his sources here

1840
01:40:39,920 --> 01:40:42,160
exposes him as a fraud.

1841
01:40:42,160 --> 01:40:45,920
We're going to move on now and consider how the bell curve measures intelligence

1842
01:40:45,920 --> 01:40:49,920
against socioeconomic status in determining one's life outcomes.

1843
01:40:49,920 --> 01:40:52,560
But I'd like you to keep in mind, if possible,

1844
01:40:52,560 --> 01:40:55,040
several of the things we've talked about so far.

1845
01:40:55,040 --> 01:40:57,680
The difficulty in defining intelligence.

1846
01:40:57,680 --> 01:41:00,480
The difficulties in testing for intelligence.

1847
01:41:00,480 --> 01:41:04,160
The bell curve's missing genetic evidence for IQ.

1848
01:41:04,160 --> 01:41:06,880
And of course, the incredibly shoddy sources

1849
01:41:06,880 --> 01:41:10,560
that Hernstein and Murray are apparently willing to accept.

1850
01:41:10,560 --> 01:41:14,000
When we see a graph measuring intelligence against environment,

1851
01:41:14,000 --> 01:41:16,880
we should not be fooled into thinking that that intelligence

1852
01:41:16,880 --> 01:41:20,160
was legitimately or accurately calculated.

1853
01:41:20,160 --> 01:41:21,440
Anyway, to the claim.

1854
01:41:21,440 --> 01:41:25,280
One's IQ is more important than one's social background

1855
01:41:25,280 --> 01:41:27,280
in determining one's life outcomes.

1856
01:41:27,920 --> 01:41:31,600
To address this claim, we first need to define the terms.

1857
01:41:31,600 --> 01:41:34,480
We know by now how Hernstein and Murray have been determining

1858
01:41:34,480 --> 01:41:36,720
the IQ of the people they're examining

1859
01:41:36,720 --> 01:41:40,240
by using their scores on the Armed Forces Qualifying Test.

1860
01:41:40,240 --> 01:41:43,360
But in order to make comparisons to their IQ,

1861
01:41:43,360 --> 01:41:47,840
how is the bell curve determining those people's socioeconomic status?

1862
01:41:47,840 --> 01:41:53,920
Let's take as an example poverty from Chapter 5 of the bell curve titled Poverty.

1863
01:41:53,920 --> 01:41:56,800
Hernstein and Murray want to compare low intelligence

1864
01:41:56,800 --> 01:42:00,480
with low socioeconomic status as causes for poverty

1865
01:42:00,480 --> 01:42:03,040
to figure out which is more important.

1866
01:42:03,040 --> 01:42:08,240
They use the survey respondents' AFQT scores as their data for intelligence,

1867
01:42:08,240 --> 01:42:11,760
and they use socioeconomic information provided by the respondents

1868
01:42:11,760 --> 01:42:15,840
to build what they call an index of socioeconomic status.

1869
01:42:16,640 --> 01:42:19,360
Both of these are then compared with the likelihood of the respondents

1870
01:42:19,360 --> 01:42:21,760
being below the poverty line a decade later.

1871
01:42:21,760 --> 01:42:24,560
And of course, Hernstein and Murray find that intelligence

1872
01:42:24,560 --> 01:42:26,960
is the better predictor of poverty.

1873
01:42:26,960 --> 01:42:30,240
So I guess we'd better examine exactly how Hernstein and Murray

1874
01:42:30,240 --> 01:42:33,520
constructed their index of socioeconomic status.

1875
01:42:33,520 --> 01:42:38,160
But before we get to that, I'd like to propose a question for us to answer.

1876
01:42:38,160 --> 01:42:40,960
What environmental factors would you deem important

1877
01:42:40,960 --> 01:42:44,880
with regards to the likelihood of a young person being in poverty?

1878
01:42:44,880 --> 01:42:47,760
And let's discuss a few possibilities here.

1879
01:42:47,760 --> 01:42:50,480
First up, parental socioeconomic status,

1880
01:42:50,480 --> 01:42:55,360
which is usually defined as their level of education, occupation, and income.

1881
01:42:55,360 --> 01:42:58,000
I think we'd all agree that is fairly important.

1882
01:42:58,000 --> 01:43:01,680
Families that have a larger income are less likely to be in poverty.

1883
01:43:01,680 --> 01:43:04,640
Better educated parents are more likely to have better jobs

1884
01:43:04,640 --> 01:43:07,200
and therefore less likely to have children in poverty.

1885
01:43:07,200 --> 01:43:08,960
This is rather straightforward.

1886
01:43:08,960 --> 01:43:11,280
Family composition is important.

1887
01:43:11,280 --> 01:43:13,840
A family with a particular income and living space

1888
01:43:13,840 --> 01:43:16,720
stretched to take care of six children, say,

1889
01:43:16,720 --> 01:43:20,160
is gonna have a harder time than a family with the same income and living space

1890
01:43:20,160 --> 01:43:22,480
but only one child to take care of.

1891
01:43:22,480 --> 01:43:24,960
So number of siblings is important,

1892
01:43:24,960 --> 01:43:29,200
as is whether or not the individual was raised in a two-parent family.

1893
01:43:29,200 --> 01:43:31,680
Two parents typically means more resources

1894
01:43:31,680 --> 01:43:34,080
and therefore less chance of being in poverty.

1895
01:43:34,080 --> 01:43:36,960
The area where someone lives is very important.

1896
01:43:36,960 --> 01:43:40,960
One family with a particular income might have a very different living experience

1897
01:43:40,960 --> 01:43:45,120
to another family with the same income that lives in a different area.

1898
01:43:45,120 --> 01:43:47,520
And this could be for a variety of reasons.

1899
01:43:47,520 --> 01:43:52,640
Average living expenses like rent, food, and other costs that vary from place to place,

1900
01:43:52,640 --> 01:43:55,760
the average crime rate, the unemployment rate,

1901
01:43:55,760 --> 01:43:59,600
that can be very important for determining one's chance of being in poverty.

1902
01:43:59,600 --> 01:44:01,200
Seems fairly obvious to mention,

1903
01:44:01,200 --> 01:44:03,920
but you're gonna have an easier time finding an income

1904
01:44:03,920 --> 01:44:07,680
in an area with many jobs than an area with few jobs.

1905
01:44:07,680 --> 01:44:11,680
Another reason the area someone lives is important to us here is school quality,

1906
01:44:11,680 --> 01:44:13,600
which should be particularly noteworthy,

1907
01:44:13,600 --> 01:44:17,040
given that we're measuring all of this against performance on an academic test.

1908
01:44:17,680 --> 01:44:20,400
How long someone stays in school is also important,

1909
01:44:20,400 --> 01:44:22,800
and how many years of education they completed

1910
01:44:22,800 --> 01:44:26,480
both before and after taking the armed forces qualifying test.

1911
01:44:26,480 --> 01:44:30,640
Familial wealth is important, and this is a separate issue to income.

1912
01:44:30,640 --> 01:44:32,400
One person with a particular income,

1913
01:44:32,400 --> 01:44:36,720
whose rich parents bought them a house and a car and paid their way through college,

1914
01:44:36,720 --> 01:44:40,160
is gonna have a different experience to a person on the same income,

1915
01:44:40,160 --> 01:44:43,440
but who has to pay off debt related to all of those things.

1916
01:44:44,000 --> 01:44:47,120
Overall, economic trends can be very important.

1917
01:44:47,120 --> 01:44:50,560
You are more likely to be in poverty during a recession.

1918
01:44:50,560 --> 01:44:53,520
The reason that the poverty rate increases during recessions

1919
01:44:53,520 --> 01:44:57,440
is not because everyone collectively loses a few IQ points, is it?

1920
01:44:58,000 --> 01:45:02,000
And the effects of recession are felt unequally across economic classes

1921
01:45:02,000 --> 01:45:03,920
and different geographical areas.

1922
01:45:04,480 --> 01:45:06,560
One's gender is important.

1923
01:45:06,560 --> 01:45:10,000
Women, for example, are more likely to be in poverty than men are.

1924
01:45:10,000 --> 01:45:14,880
Now, whether you believe this is because women have lower genetic IQs than men do,

1925
01:45:14,880 --> 01:45:18,640
or you're sensible and you believe it's because of environmental reasons,

1926
01:45:18,640 --> 01:45:19,840
it is the case.

1927
01:45:19,840 --> 01:45:22,160
I should note here that I'm excluding race

1928
01:45:22,160 --> 01:45:24,560
because this chapter of the bell curve concerns itself

1929
01:45:24,560 --> 01:45:27,680
with only the white respondents to the AFQT.

1930
01:45:27,680 --> 01:45:30,160
Your health is important, of course.

1931
01:45:30,160 --> 01:45:33,760
People with disabilities, for instance, are more likely to be in poverty,

1932
01:45:33,760 --> 01:45:37,600
and particularly in the US, the cost of medical care and health insurance

1933
01:45:37,600 --> 01:45:41,040
can massively affect someone's likelihood of being in poverty.

1934
01:45:41,040 --> 01:45:44,640
And we could go on listing things, but we will arbitrarily stop here.

1935
01:45:44,880 --> 01:45:46,720
I trust you get the point by now.

1936
01:45:46,720 --> 01:45:49,040
There are lots of different things to consider

1937
01:45:49,040 --> 01:45:52,000
when attempting to determine how someone's environment

1938
01:45:52,000 --> 01:45:54,480
might contribute to them being in poverty.

1939
01:45:54,480 --> 01:45:56,880
Which brings us back to the bell curve.

1940
01:45:56,880 --> 01:45:59,040
Which of the various factors on this list

1941
01:45:59,040 --> 01:46:01,280
did Hernstein and Murray think were important

1942
01:46:01,280 --> 01:46:05,360
with regards to the likelihood of a young person being in poverty?

1943
01:46:06,400 --> 01:46:07,280
The first one.

1944
01:46:07,920 --> 01:46:09,120
Yep, that's all.

1945
01:46:09,760 --> 01:46:12,720
Hernstein and Murray's consideration of environmental factors

1946
01:46:12,720 --> 01:46:15,920
extends to parental education, income, and occupation.

1947
01:46:15,920 --> 01:46:16,880
That's all.

1948
01:46:16,880 --> 01:46:18,160
As far as they're concerned,

1949
01:46:18,160 --> 01:46:20,960
with regards to the determining predictors of poverty,

1950
01:46:20,960 --> 01:46:23,280
all the other things on this list have no effect.

1951
01:46:23,280 --> 01:46:25,040
Your family's wealth has no effect.

1952
01:46:25,040 --> 01:46:27,360
Family composition, the area where you live,

1953
01:46:27,360 --> 01:46:31,760
the quality of the school you went to, the crime rate, all irrelevant.

1954
01:46:31,760 --> 01:46:35,520
What they have done here is substitute environmental factors

1955
01:46:35,520 --> 01:46:38,240
for parental socioeconomic status,

1956
01:46:38,240 --> 01:46:41,680
which is a much narrower category of variables.

1957
01:46:41,680 --> 01:46:45,360
They simply add together parental education, income, and occupation,

1958
01:46:45,360 --> 01:46:49,760
call that parental socioeconomic status, and plot it against IQ.

1959
01:46:49,760 --> 01:46:51,680
And this is the graph they come up with.

1960
01:46:51,680 --> 01:46:54,800
The comparative roles of IQ and parental SES

1961
01:46:54,800 --> 01:46:58,560
in determining whether young white adults are below the poverty line.

1962
01:46:58,560 --> 01:47:01,840
It shows that people with low IQs are more likely to be in poverty

1963
01:47:01,840 --> 01:47:04,400
than people whose parents had a low SES.

1964
01:47:04,400 --> 01:47:05,760
And also the reverse.

1965
01:47:05,760 --> 01:47:08,400
High IQ people are less likely to be in poverty

1966
01:47:08,400 --> 01:47:11,200
than people whose parents had a high SES.

1967
01:47:11,200 --> 01:47:13,520
Cognitive ability is more important

1968
01:47:13,520 --> 01:47:17,760
than parental socioeconomic status in determining poverty, they say.

1969
01:47:17,760 --> 01:47:19,520
But of course, as we have seen,

1970
01:47:19,520 --> 01:47:23,840
their consideration of environmental factors here is laughably narrow.

1971
01:47:24,400 --> 01:47:26,640
They only want to consider as valid things

1972
01:47:26,640 --> 01:47:29,840
that fall under their definition of parental SES.

1973
01:47:29,840 --> 01:47:33,040
And they ignore all the other relevant environmental factors.

1974
01:47:33,600 --> 01:47:37,680
What would happen to this graph if we also considered the various other things

1975
01:47:37,680 --> 01:47:40,880
that Hernstein and Murray leave out of their analysis?

1976
01:47:40,960 --> 01:47:44,640
Now, I don't know how to do regression analysis, unfortunately,

1977
01:47:44,640 --> 01:47:47,840
but the book Inequality by Design was written by some people

1978
01:47:47,840 --> 01:47:50,000
who do know how to do regression analysis,

1979
01:47:50,000 --> 01:47:52,880
and they do exactly what we're looking for here.

1980
01:47:52,880 --> 01:47:57,600
Firstly, they recreate Hernstein and Murray's calculations using their data.

1981
01:47:57,600 --> 01:48:01,040
They then use the National Longitudinal Survey of Youth Responses

1982
01:48:01,040 --> 01:48:04,880
to add more environmental data to the analysis.

1983
01:48:04,880 --> 01:48:10,080
Their first updated graph changes parental SES to parental home environment,

1984
01:48:10,080 --> 01:48:12,880
adding for consideration things like the number of siblings

1985
01:48:12,880 --> 01:48:15,360
and whether the household has two parents.

1986
01:48:15,360 --> 01:48:20,800
As we can see, AFQT score is still more important than parental home environment,

1987
01:48:20,800 --> 01:48:23,680
but now the two are much closer together.

1988
01:48:23,680 --> 01:48:27,280
Next up, they add community environment to home environment,

1989
01:48:27,280 --> 01:48:30,720
considering the region where the respondent lived when they took the test

1990
01:48:30,720 --> 01:48:32,640
and the school that they attended.

1991
01:48:32,640 --> 01:48:37,280
Doing this, we see that AFQT score and social environment are now equal.

1992
01:48:38,000 --> 01:48:41,840
Next, they add for consideration the number of years of education

1993
01:48:41,840 --> 01:48:44,000
of the respondents to the survey.

1994
01:48:44,000 --> 01:48:46,480
And by now, the AFQT score has slipped

1995
01:48:46,480 --> 01:48:49,840
below the combined environmental factors in importance.

1996
01:48:49,840 --> 01:48:54,000
Using the same statistical methods and data set as the bell curve,

1997
01:48:54,000 --> 01:48:57,760
Inequality by Design's analysis shows that environmental factors

1998
01:48:57,760 --> 01:49:00,480
are more important than AFQT score

1999
01:49:00,480 --> 01:49:03,440
in determining the probability of being in poverty.

2000
01:49:03,440 --> 01:49:06,800
And this is shown using only the limited data available

2001
01:49:06,800 --> 01:49:09,840
in the National Longitudinal Survey of Youth, remember.

2002
01:49:09,840 --> 01:49:13,120
Inequality by Design adds to the analysis only a few

2003
01:49:13,120 --> 01:49:18,160
of the conceivable socioeconomic factors that are ignored by Hernstein and Murray.

2004
01:49:18,160 --> 01:49:21,920
If we were to continue adding in available factors to consider,

2005
01:49:21,920 --> 01:49:25,120
the effect of IQ would get weaker and weaker.

2006
01:49:25,120 --> 01:49:28,960
And lest you think Inequality by Design's analysis was a one-off,

2007
01:49:28,960 --> 01:49:34,240
the authors of Intelligence, Genes, and Success also reanalyzed the NLSY data,

2008
01:49:34,240 --> 01:49:36,640
and with regards to how much cognitive ability

2009
01:49:36,640 --> 01:49:40,800
accounts for differences in wages between people, say the following.

2010
01:49:40,800 --> 01:49:44,640
However, our results conflict with the predictions of Hernstein and Murray.

2011
01:49:44,640 --> 01:49:48,240
Ability factors other than G are economically useful.

2012
01:49:48,240 --> 01:49:51,920
Compared with education, family background, and region of residence,

2013
01:49:51,920 --> 01:49:54,880
G explains little of the variance in wages.

2014
01:49:54,880 --> 01:49:58,800
If there exists some X factor that can explain the large residuals

2015
01:49:58,800 --> 01:50:03,040
common in wage regressions, it is not measured cognitive ability.

2016
01:50:03,040 --> 01:50:08,000
In summary, our re-analyses of the NLSY data originally analyzed by Hernstein and Murray

2017
01:50:08,000 --> 01:50:11,440
show measured cognitive ability is correlated with wages,

2018
01:50:11,440 --> 01:50:16,080
but explains little of the variance in wages across individuals and time.

2019
01:50:16,080 --> 01:50:21,280
Later in this chapter, Hernstein and Murray use this same narrowly defined parental SES

2020
01:50:21,280 --> 01:50:25,520
to consider which young people will drop out of school, get a college degree,

2021
01:50:25,520 --> 01:50:29,920
be unemployed, have children out of wedlock, be on welfare, and so on.

2022
01:50:29,920 --> 01:50:33,360
To be fair, sometimes they do add other factors to consider,

2023
01:50:33,360 --> 01:50:39,360
but again, only when they personally, subjectively, decide those factors are important.

2024
01:50:39,360 --> 01:50:44,160
All their comparisons between IQ and SES that inform their later policy proposals

2025
01:50:44,160 --> 01:50:47,440
are based upon this calculated decision to not consider

2026
01:50:47,440 --> 01:50:50,400
the full range of relevant environmental factors.

2027
01:50:50,400 --> 01:50:54,480
And there's two other important points that we have to keep in mind here.

2028
01:50:54,480 --> 01:50:58,160
The first is that we have been assuming that AFQT score

2029
01:50:58,160 --> 01:51:00,960
is a legitimate stand-in for cognitive ability,

2030
01:51:00,960 --> 01:51:05,520
which, given all the potential problems with intelligence testing we've already discussed,

2031
01:51:05,520 --> 01:51:07,120
is a bit of a stretch.

2032
01:51:07,120 --> 01:51:11,680
The second thing we need to remember is that Hernstein and Murray's estimation of IQ

2033
01:51:11,680 --> 01:51:15,600
is that it is only 60% genetically heritable.

2034
01:51:15,600 --> 01:51:19,680
That would mean, according to their flawed understanding of heritability anyway,

2035
01:51:19,680 --> 01:51:26,720
that 40% of the IQ score in their calculations originated from environmental factors.

2036
01:51:26,720 --> 01:51:32,320
Considering all these things together, the case for IQ here is looking incredibly flimsy.

2037
01:51:32,320 --> 01:51:37,600
So as we've seen, once you add more factors to consider, environment trumps IQ.

2038
01:51:38,240 --> 01:51:43,200
So we now have to ask, is this a legitimate thing to do, statistically speaking?

2039
01:51:43,200 --> 01:51:46,720
The bell curve anticipates being criticized in this manner.

2040
01:51:46,720 --> 01:51:50,880
In a section titled, But What About Other Explanations?, they write,

2041
01:51:50,880 --> 01:51:55,680
We can already hear critics saying, if only they'd added this other variable to the analysis,

2042
01:51:55,680 --> 01:51:58,560
they would have seen that intelligence has nothing to do with x.

2043
01:51:59,200 --> 01:52:03,440
At this point, however, statistical analysis can become a bottomless pit.

2044
01:52:03,440 --> 01:52:07,840
It is not uncommon in technical journals to read articles built around the estimated effects

2045
01:52:07,840 --> 01:52:10,560
of a dozen or more independent variables.

2046
01:52:10,560 --> 01:52:15,280
Sometimes the entire set of variables is loaded into a single regression equation.

2047
01:52:15,280 --> 01:52:19,760
Sometimes sets of equations are used, modeling even more complex relationships

2048
01:52:19,760 --> 01:52:23,600
in which all the variables can exert mutual effects on one another.

2049
01:52:23,600 --> 01:52:25,280
Why should we not press forward?

2050
01:52:25,280 --> 01:52:30,480
Why not also ask if religious background has an effect on the decision to go on welfare, for example?

2051
01:52:30,480 --> 01:52:34,880
It's an interesting question, as are 50 others that might come to mind.

2052
01:52:34,880 --> 01:52:37,680
This is the first of two defenses by Hanstein and Murray,

2053
01:52:37,680 --> 01:52:41,920
where they argue that it would just be too complicated to consider all the factors.

2054
01:52:42,480 --> 01:52:48,000
Why there could be 50 environmental variables affecting someone's likelihood of being in poverty,

2055
01:52:48,000 --> 01:52:49,600
that's just too many.

2056
01:52:49,600 --> 01:52:51,200
It would be too complex.

2057
01:52:51,200 --> 01:52:54,000
Our graph wouldn't make any sense if we did that.

2058
01:52:54,000 --> 01:52:58,080
So instead of 50, we're just gonna consider, I don't know, two.

2059
01:52:58,080 --> 01:53:01,200
This is a result of treating the method of investigation

2060
01:53:01,200 --> 01:53:04,480
as more important than getting accurate results.

2061
01:53:04,480 --> 01:53:08,240
If you can't use regression analysis to fairly compare IQ

2062
01:53:08,240 --> 01:53:11,760
to all the relevant environmental factors, don't.

2063
01:53:12,320 --> 01:53:14,880
You know, you don't actually have to do this.

2064
01:53:15,440 --> 01:53:19,440
Hanstein and Murray's second defense is even more telling than the first.

2065
01:53:20,080 --> 01:53:22,800
Our principle was to explore additional dynamics

2066
01:53:22,800 --> 01:53:26,480
when there was another factor that was not only conceivably important,

2067
01:53:26,480 --> 01:53:29,440
but for clear logical reasons might be important

2068
01:53:29,440 --> 01:53:32,800
because of dynamics having little or nothing to do with IQ.

2069
01:53:33,680 --> 01:53:35,440
This last proviso is crucial,

2070
01:53:35,440 --> 01:53:38,560
for one of the most common misuses of regression analysis

2071
01:53:38,560 --> 01:53:40,800
is to introduce an additional variable

2072
01:53:40,800 --> 01:53:46,800
that in reality is mostly another expression of variables that are already in the equation.

2073
01:53:46,800 --> 01:53:50,320
So what Hanstein and Murray are saying is that they dismissed variables

2074
01:53:50,320 --> 01:53:54,480
if they deemed them to merely be mostly expressions of IQ,

2075
01:53:54,480 --> 01:53:56,640
which is already in the equation.

2076
01:53:57,440 --> 01:53:59,440
They only considered additional factors

2077
01:53:59,440 --> 01:54:01,760
when they had little or nothing to do with IQ

2078
01:54:01,760 --> 01:54:04,560
and were, quote, conceivably important.

2079
01:54:04,560 --> 01:54:06,480
Which should lead us to ask a question.

2080
01:54:06,480 --> 01:54:11,520
How are Hanstein and Murray deciding which variables are conceivably important?

2081
01:54:11,520 --> 01:54:14,880
And how are they deciding how much they have to do with IQ?

2082
01:54:14,880 --> 01:54:18,000
And the answer, of course, is subjectively.

2083
01:54:18,000 --> 01:54:22,240
They're only considering things that they reckon are important.

2084
01:54:22,240 --> 01:54:25,440
You see, the problem with Hanstein and Murray dismissing variables

2085
01:54:25,440 --> 01:54:30,400
that they have subjectively decided are merely expressions of cognitive ability here

2086
01:54:30,400 --> 01:54:36,000
is that they think that socioeconomic status itself is an expression of cognitive ability.

2087
01:54:36,000 --> 01:54:41,200
Later in the book, when criticizing the practice of controlling for SES between racial groups,

2088
01:54:41,200 --> 01:54:41,920
they write,

2089
01:54:41,920 --> 01:54:47,040
the difficulty comes in interpreting what it means to control for socioeconomic status.

2090
01:54:47,040 --> 01:54:50,320
Matching the status of the groups is usually justified on the grounds

2091
01:54:50,320 --> 01:54:55,440
that the scores people earn are caused to some extent by their socioeconomic status.

2092
01:54:55,440 --> 01:54:59,360
So if we want to see the real or authentic difference between them,

2093
01:54:59,360 --> 01:55:02,240
the contribution of status must be excluded.

2094
01:55:02,240 --> 01:55:07,600
The trouble is that socioeconomic status is also a result of cognitive ability,

2095
01:55:07,600 --> 01:55:09,680
as people of high and low cognitive ability

2096
01:55:09,680 --> 01:55:13,760
move to correspondingly high and low places in the socioeconomic continuum.

2097
01:55:13,760 --> 01:55:16,000
Now, this is circular logic.

2098
01:55:16,000 --> 01:55:19,840
Hanstein and Murray claim to be limiting which factors they're considering

2099
01:55:19,840 --> 01:55:24,240
to avoid including those which are merely expressions of other factors,

2100
01:55:24,240 --> 01:55:29,600
but their main comparison here is between cognitive ability and socioeconomic status,

2101
01:55:29,600 --> 01:55:33,760
which they elsewhere argue is a result of cognitive ability.

2102
01:55:33,760 --> 01:55:40,000
Using this framework, where cognitive ability determines both IQ and socioeconomic status,

2103
01:55:40,000 --> 01:55:43,120
the whole series of comparisons from this chapter of the bell curve

2104
01:55:43,120 --> 01:55:45,440
seems cynical and unnecessary.

2105
01:55:45,520 --> 01:55:50,000
Hanstein and Murray have already decided what conclusion they're gonna come to,

2106
01:55:50,000 --> 01:55:54,080
that cognitive ability is more important than all the other variables,

2107
01:55:54,080 --> 01:55:58,240
and all their statistical comparisons read as them just going through the motions

2108
01:55:58,240 --> 01:55:59,680
to get that result.

2109
01:55:59,680 --> 01:56:04,880
In simply declaring socioeconomic status the result of cognitive ability,

2110
01:56:04,880 --> 01:56:08,720
the bell curve brings to mind the chicken and egg problem here.

2111
01:56:09,280 --> 01:56:11,440
You see, a lot of disagreements over IQ

2112
01:56:11,440 --> 01:56:14,960
stem from different interpretations of the same data.

2113
01:56:14,960 --> 01:56:18,320
Let's say you do a study which proves a strong positive correlation

2114
01:56:18,320 --> 01:56:22,720
between the amount of time someone has spent in education and their IQ,

2115
01:56:22,720 --> 01:56:25,840
and you present those findings to two groups of people.

2116
01:56:25,840 --> 01:56:28,720
One group that favors environmental explanations

2117
01:56:28,720 --> 01:56:31,600
and one that favors genetic explanations.

2118
01:56:31,600 --> 01:56:34,720
Now, of course, the environmentalists will say,

2119
01:56:34,720 --> 01:56:36,960
this result makes perfect sense.

2120
01:56:36,960 --> 01:56:39,840
The longer you're in education, the more things you learn,

2121
01:56:39,840 --> 01:56:43,920
the better you get at answering the sorts of questions that show up on IQ tests,

2122
01:56:43,920 --> 01:56:48,080
the more familiar you are with taking academic tests in the first place.

2123
01:56:48,080 --> 01:56:51,200
IQ clearly stems from environment.

2124
01:56:51,200 --> 01:56:54,240
The genetic-minded folks, on the other hand, will say,

2125
01:56:54,240 --> 01:56:57,280
of course, this result makes perfect sense.

2126
01:56:57,280 --> 01:57:00,480
People with higher IQs favor an academic environment,

2127
01:57:00,480 --> 01:57:02,800
and they're more likely to stay in school longer

2128
01:57:02,800 --> 01:57:05,200
because that's the smarter thing to do.

2129
01:57:05,200 --> 01:57:07,680
Since they have higher IQs to begin with,

2130
01:57:07,680 --> 01:57:09,920
they will naturally make better choices.

2131
01:57:09,920 --> 01:57:13,280
Environment clearly stems from IQ.

2132
01:57:13,280 --> 01:57:16,560
So which came first, the chicken or the egg?

2133
01:57:16,560 --> 01:57:18,800
Environment or cognitive ability?

2134
01:57:18,800 --> 01:57:20,800
We can phrase this two ways.

2135
01:57:20,800 --> 01:57:24,320
A parent's higher cognitive ability leads to a better environment,

2136
01:57:24,320 --> 01:57:28,080
which again leads to a higher cognitive ability in their children.

2137
01:57:28,080 --> 01:57:30,240
Or we can say that a better environment

2138
01:57:30,240 --> 01:57:32,560
leads to a parent's higher cognitive ability,

2139
01:57:32,560 --> 01:57:35,920
which then produces a better environment for their children.

2140
01:57:35,920 --> 01:57:38,720
But both of these ways of phrasing are merely presenting

2141
01:57:38,720 --> 01:57:43,600
a segment of the overall environment-cognitive ability logic chain.

2142
01:57:43,600 --> 01:57:46,160
The bell curve solves the conundrum of whether

2143
01:57:46,160 --> 01:57:49,360
cognitive ability or environment should come first by saying...

2144
01:57:50,080 --> 01:57:51,200
cognitive ability.

2145
01:57:51,920 --> 01:57:52,720
That's first.

2146
01:57:52,720 --> 01:57:56,080
We like that one the most, so that's the one that comes first.

2147
01:57:56,080 --> 01:57:58,480
But of course, this is completely arbitrary,

2148
01:57:58,480 --> 01:58:01,440
and also, ultimately, incorrect.

2149
01:58:01,440 --> 01:58:05,120
To understand this, we need to talk about another of the main problems

2150
01:58:05,120 --> 01:58:08,000
with the scientific arguments of the bell curve,

2151
01:58:08,000 --> 01:58:11,920
which is that Herrnstein and Murray are conspicuously uninterested

2152
01:58:11,920 --> 01:58:14,880
in the causes of the things that they're talking about.

2153
01:58:15,840 --> 01:58:18,720
Much of the bell curve, for instance, is concerned with proving

2154
01:58:18,720 --> 01:58:21,840
that there are substantial differences in cognitive ability

2155
01:58:21,840 --> 01:58:24,400
between different designated racial groups.

2156
01:58:24,400 --> 01:58:28,160
But what Herrnstein and Murray never seriously concern themselves with

2157
01:58:28,160 --> 01:58:31,120
is why this supposed divergence happened.

2158
01:58:31,120 --> 01:58:35,520
Population groups don't evolve to be different for no reason, do they?

2159
01:58:35,520 --> 01:58:38,960
If one group developed better cognitive skills than another group,

2160
01:58:38,960 --> 01:58:40,960
there would have to be some mechanism there

2161
01:58:40,960 --> 01:58:44,400
that was leading to higher cognitive ability in that group,

2162
01:58:44,400 --> 01:58:48,240
or, I suppose, leading to lower cognitive ability in the other group.

2163
01:58:48,240 --> 01:58:51,280
Now, this could simply be direct evolutionary pressure,

2164
01:58:51,280 --> 01:58:54,320
as in different levels of cognitive ability in different groups

2165
01:58:54,320 --> 01:58:56,800
are being directly selected for.

2166
01:58:56,800 --> 01:58:59,520
Or it could be an indirect, unintended effect

2167
01:58:59,520 --> 01:59:01,680
of a different trait being selected for,

2168
01:59:01,680 --> 01:59:03,840
or some sort of genetic drift,

2169
01:59:03,840 --> 01:59:06,320
as generations of different population groups

2170
01:59:06,320 --> 01:59:08,320
are isolated enough from each other

2171
01:59:08,320 --> 01:59:11,360
to develop in significantly different ways.

2172
01:59:11,360 --> 01:59:15,120
Whatever the reason, though, there would have to be a reason.

2173
01:59:15,120 --> 01:59:18,080
And we should expect a scientist attempting to argue

2174
01:59:18,080 --> 01:59:21,360
for a substantial difference in ability between different groups

2175
01:59:21,360 --> 01:59:26,560
to therefore maybe be interested in exactly why this difference came about, right?

2176
01:59:27,120 --> 01:59:29,520
One of the only times that Herrnstein and Murray

2177
01:59:29,520 --> 01:59:31,440
show any interest in this question

2178
01:59:31,440 --> 01:59:33,920
is in Appendix Five, where they discuss the work

2179
01:59:33,920 --> 01:59:37,200
of Canadian psychologist J. Philippe Rushton,

2180
01:59:37,200 --> 01:59:41,760
who wrote the book Race, Evolution, and Behavior in 1995.

2181
01:59:41,760 --> 01:59:46,720
Rushton alleges that brain and genital size are inversely related,

2182
01:59:46,720 --> 01:59:50,800
and that larger genitals correlate with an increased fertility.

2183
01:59:50,800 --> 01:59:55,280
So at some point, different designated racial groups diverged from one another

2184
01:59:55,280 --> 01:59:59,760
and developed different traits according to some sort of trade-off system.

2185
01:59:59,760 --> 02:00:02,560
So it's like a computer game where you have limited points

2186
02:00:02,560 --> 02:00:04,240
to put into your starting stats,

2187
02:00:04,240 --> 02:00:08,640
only here the starting stats are int and genital size.

2188
02:00:09,440 --> 02:00:14,400
In 1988, Rushton was reprimanded by the University of Western Ontario

2189
02:00:14,400 --> 02:00:17,120
for carrying out two particular studies.

2190
02:00:17,120 --> 02:00:19,760
He surveyed first-year psychology students

2191
02:00:19,760 --> 02:00:22,960
and then male customers at a Toronto shopping mall,

2192
02:00:22,960 --> 02:00:25,600
asking them questions about their sex lives,

2193
02:00:25,600 --> 02:00:27,440
the size of their penises,

2194
02:00:27,440 --> 02:00:30,560
and the exact distance that they ejaculate.

2195
02:00:31,440 --> 02:00:34,000
Now, I can only speak for myself here,

2196
02:00:34,640 --> 02:00:36,640
but I can't say I've ever measured.

2197
02:00:37,760 --> 02:00:42,080
One therefore wonders how reliable this self-reported data could be.

2198
02:00:42,800 --> 02:00:45,760
Or, who knows, maybe I'm the anomaly here.

